## 9. Rollback Strategy

Sprint 4 is **purely additive** on the agent layer (one return-shape change) and **replaces** the I/O layer. Rollback to Sprint 3 state is cheap.

**Recommended commit structure:**
- Commit A: `feat(server): add Express entrypoint with routing-aware /api/chat` (Task 1+4 + orchestrator edit + delete index.ts)
- Commit B: `feat(ui): add vanilla chat interface` (Task 2)
- Commit C: `feat(ui): add sample prompt buttons` (Task 3)

**Fast-rollback recipes:**

| Scenario | Action |
|----------|--------|
| UI bugs, server fine | `git revert <Commit C>` (buttons) or `<Commit B>` (full UI) |
| Server broken, UI fine | `git revert <Commit A>` ‚Äî restores CLI. Then need to also revert B/C since they reference the deleted `index.ts` via‚Ä¶ (they don't ‚Äî HTML is self-contained). So just `git revert A` ‚Äî UI becomes dead HTML in `public/` until fixed. |
| Entire sprint needs to be undone | `git revert` commits C ‚Üí B ‚Üí A in that order |

**Sprint 3 restoration:** Reverting Commit A restores `src/index.ts` and the original `runOrchestrator` string return type. Tasks B/C leave `public/index.html` orphaned (harmless dead file).

**Guardrail:** Do NOT modify `runAgent.ts`, `researchAgent.ts`, `toolDispatcher.ts`, `tools.ts`, `toolHandlers.ts`, `conversationState.ts`, `prompts.ts`, `env.ts`, `anthropic.ts`. The only agent-layer file that changes is `orchestrator.ts`, and only its return shape ‚Äî the classification/delegation behavior stays verbatim.

