Zero change to classification logic, delegation targets, or logging. Only the return value wraps into an object.

**`src/server.ts` skeleton:**
```ts
import express, { Request, Response } from "express";
import path from "path";
import "./config/env"; // triggers API key validation at startup
import { runOrchestrator } from "./agent/orchestrator";

const PORT = 5002;
const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(express.static(path.join(__dirname, "..", "public")));

app.post("/api/chat", async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  const prompt = typeof req.body?.prompt === "string" ? req.body.prompt.trim() : "";
  if (!prompt) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: "prompt is required and must be a non-empty string" });
  }
  try {
    const result = await runOrchestrator(prompt);
    res.json(result); // { response, agentType }
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("Orchestrator error:", err);
    res.status(500).json({ error: err instanceof Error ? err.message : "unknown error" });
  }
});

app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`üåê Managed Agents POC ‚Üí http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```
Notes:
- `import "./config/env"` triggers the API-key validation check at boot (fail-fast). Good.
- `express.static` handles GET / automatically (serves `public/index.html`).
- Explicit POST validation on `prompt`. Returns 400 on bad input, 500 on runtime failures, 200 with JSON on success.
- No CORS middleware ‚Äî same-origin, not needed.

